Republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers this as a myth, claiming that election fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of U.S. governments passed new laws starting in 2009 making the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon gained scale after the November 2010 elections, which added 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of voting rights in 41 states were introduced during the year 2011.
New electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID card and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce the periods of early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on the day of the election, and deprive citizens with a judicial record of their right to vote.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first state to make such a requirement.
In 2008, the U.S. Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana Act.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card like the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people in the age of voting, do not possess photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
Moreover, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity card.
However, it often costs more than $100 to obtain the required identity card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not possess the required photo ID card.
much more .
Students, from voters considered to be voting more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their photo ID card issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use cards issued by these clubs to vote.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to make such a request.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Spanish voting.
Two out of three Spanish voters favour the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers sponsored in 2011 laws abolishing voter registration on election day in eight states.
Furthermore, they restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped register about 10 million citizens.
However, measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the registration rate of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of state voters.
It was the same with the Spanish.
These represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites who made up 76% of the voters represented only 46% of the voters voting in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills were blocked by Democratic governors’ vetoes.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to reduce the damage in part.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring a photo ID card.
However, the new rules will undoubtedly make it harder to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed and see it as an obvious goal of influencing the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that passed these laws represented 171 of the 270 votes needed for the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
