The Higgs Boson Decorated
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a lot of emotion, last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the universe, nothing but that.
And then, it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model – our best, or “less worse” explanation of the nature and behavior of matter – but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that this is really Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we hold an authentic new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Furthermore, new data revealed this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be absolutely sure.
Let’s assume, however, that this is Higgs, since the chances of mistaking seem small, and let’s see what it is.
There is, in this low world, a fatally inevitable law that says that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule – and don’t try too hard, you’ll hurt yourself.
Even though particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: the Pauli exclusion principle, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting largely of some of their characteristics.
Therefore, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other are the bosons, a dirty band of anarchists who have no respect for anything – at least not for that principle, which means that they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons then divide into two groups, according to the (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) site The Particle Adventure, of the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not address here, and the "force particles", through which the great forces of nature spread and to which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
These bosons, it should be pointed out here, are not all so exotic beasts as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "light particle" that is the "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field in that specific place, a bit like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this “disturbance” a electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing more than a photon – and therefore, one of the “force-bearing” bosons.
A more stable area
The same goes for the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, that must be "disturbed" in order for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it must reach very, very high energies, a bit as if it were a frozen pond of which only a very large rock could scratch the surface.
That’s why it takes a huge particle accelerator like that of CERN – the Large Hadron Collider is a ring of 27 km perimeter! – to such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
Not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don't - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold onto a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (such as the photon, yours) do not.
Now, what “can” all this research bring, Mrs. Plamondon asks?
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to scan any discrepancy between MS observations and predictions.
They are also many to wish that one finds it, because the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and clog some holes in the Model.
This, it must be said, still has huge deficiencies, offering no explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the universe's matter (re-oops!).
However, such differences have not been found at CERN so far.
Implications
The repercussions of these researches on the daily life of Mr. and Mrs. All-Le-Monde, they are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be no one.
Keep in mind: at the very beginning of the 1960s, the laser pioneers at the Bell Laboratories did not suspect the revolution that their work was about to trigger.
They were interviewing scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsated) in 1962 - has already told us - initially the laser was seen rather as a "lab gadget".
Imagine it...
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work in optics.
This sensor, although it wasn’t at all its original intention, now serves as an “eye” to all digital cameras in the world, and won the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it means that, really, you never know...
Palliative Care – The Best Way to Die
With its Commission to Die in Dignity, Quebec has recently debated the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate is expected to resume soon as a bill is being prepared.
However, there is still much to be done in this crucial area.
He tried to look at it more closely.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that ravaged him had left him a two-year break.
"They had given me five years to live, I turned seven," he said, half-figue half-raisin, lying in his bed at the palliative care home Victor-Gadbois, from Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for that,” he says.
The disease does its job: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the toilet alone, and even eating alone.
Attacked before an appetizing lunch, he agrees to allow himself to help eat, resigned.
Brave, he even smiles, talks to strangers who are busy around him, brings him his medicines, offers him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My greatest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it’s humiliating,” he confesses.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this illness.
“Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man is staying,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois House.
Returning to the childhood stage, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
“It depends on the person’s ability to accept regression,” he says.
Because, in the opinion of many people working in palliative care, great moments take place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses surrounding them no longer provides so-called “curative” care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die “conscious and suffocated.”
But the illness made me discover my children.
“I have good kids,” she added.
“I don’t have any more wishes in life,” she said, before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
In the coming days, she is expected to visit her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, together with a group of volunteers, body care and food assistance are provided.
Palliative care is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 inhabitants.
It’s hard to know that we will all die someday.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, says Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors at the house.
Whether on the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The deceased will be accepted to provide oral care with brandy or Pepsi, as requested.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served a beer to Mr. X, who died during the night.
This morning, it is his son who will finish the beer at the deceased’s feet.
“We help relatives as much as patients,” says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
In the house of Victor-Gadbois, the days follow one another but are not similar.
Alongside a 93-year-old man who tastes his last family gathering in the courtyard, quiet in his pillows while drinking in his honor, a 36-year-old man tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, there are still three to five beds that are occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care designed to ease suffering when a sick person has reached the terminal phase of his or her life, whether at home, in the hospital or at a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Société de soins palliatifs à domicile du Grand Montréal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care offered to cancer patients.
It is precisely this large shortage in Quebec health care that makes several doctors specializing in palliative care fear the adoption of a law framing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care summits including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has circulated to testify to their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not performing enough to ensure that everyone will have the right to quality palliative care before one agrees to proceed with euthanasia.
Recently, she said, I saw a patient spend 14 days in the emergency, in great pain, without doing anything to relieve her.
I fear that patients are asking to die only because they are not receiving adequate care.
And at the same time, several oncologists struggle with their patients until the last day, despite the worst forecasts.
Hélène Richard’s hopes of survival were already minimal when she abandoned a challenging chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping the treatment, she replied that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she said.
She told me I was finished.
Not all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for failing to access their request after they were relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in treating pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Grand Montréal Home Palliative Care Society, patients would be refractory to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which is to sleep the patient until the moment of his death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear this part of suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved always say the same phrase: “I want to die.”
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me,” it means “I want to be relieved.”
