With Bitcoin, Pay and Sell Without Banks
All the opposite of current currency exchanges, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between stakeholders.
Moreover, as often happens in these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the belief that the current monetary system, made of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible in dollars, euros...) and a secure exchange protocol in the way of BitTorrent, which allows peer-to-peer file exchange.
Approximately 200,000 transactions have already been recorded through 15,000 computers on the network.
A few thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a means of payment.
The price of bitcoin, after reaching a peak of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later, before returning today around a dozen dollars (the prices are listed on the site bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing very impressive compared to global exchanges in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) was interested in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency”, “competing with the dollar or the euro” and “similar to conventional currencies”.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currency such as “credits”, used to progress in a video game that you win by playing or that you can buy (and sometimes exchange in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this type of system.
But, every time, a central authority controls and handles trade.
With Bitcoin, all the nodes in the network are both account book depositaries, checks, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually done between two email addresses in the way of an email.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double-key encryption system.
This allows the network to verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist well in the public account book, spread across the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction into this book.
It goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers, and the winner of which, sort of a provisional central banker, will have the privilege to add this additional line.
This is a phase of file hashing, i.e. the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
Computers “take” the new transaction and add a number to it before “hacking” the set.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular footprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily check that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, to cheat, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphaned because the two have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
Therefore, the number of bitcoins in circulation is limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to one hundred millionth, leaving a margin to be used.
The difficulty of the challenge is also highlighted with each increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin were attacked and deposited bitcoins stolen.
“The vulnerability used does not affect the protocol itself,” said Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also notes the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash has this disadvantage as well.
Major actors such as Wikipedia reject donations of this nature.
Others, such as the WordPress blogging platform, support them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, from the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the account book and showed that 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, “giant salaries” were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of an educational book on this currency, believes heavily in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which come back cheaper.
The carrier also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement with merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
They just need to communicate an address that a phone can “photograph and recognize,” says Pierre Noizat, who assures he has thousands of users.
There is a general movement of challenging hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
“It will take time for Bitcoin to impose itself, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, also plans to re-evaluate the various risks, now considered high, in the event of the success of this currency.
We left Afghanistan.
And after then?
French troops have left their zone of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the US are expected to follow by the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to take possession of its territory and for the Afghans to choose their future, without expecting anything from us.
It is primarily the Afghan peasants that we have punished by considering them terrorists.
And we ourselves, with our 88 soldiers killed, and the wounded, the mutilated.
The Taliban consists of foreign extremists, former leaders who have fled to Pakistan, but often of peasants who refuse foreign armed presence, as in Soviet times.
They want to defend their traditions, ancient and archaic, even though they have been joined by jihadists, Pakistani, Arab, Uzbek, Tajik.
Tolerated, sometimes helped by local insurgents, they will no longer be, when the West becomes more discreet.
The departure of the French troops from the base of Nijrab, which I observed from the top of the hills planted with almonds thanks to French credits, was done in order.
Convoys of trucks and armoured vehicles entered Kabul without being attacked by helicopters.
There will be no Taliban invasion of Kabul by the end of 2014.
The circumstances have changed since their irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996.
Kabul was then empty, the land of fire and blood due to struggles between different factions.
Their taking control of the country was then perceived as a kind of liberation, a return to security.
The Afghans have paid the price of the obscurantism of these peasants overtaken by the al-Qaeda organization, but their situation has not improved these days.
Former Mujahideen, Afghan government and current Taliban are uniting in the desire to keep women in a lower position.
The main notables of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They turned into businessmen, seizing government land to sell it for land to build to refugees coming from Iran and Pakistan, benefiting from huge U.S. subcontracts.
They disregarded themselves; most of them did not fight themselves.
People, as I have heard in the countryside, aspire to a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave, as will those who have been able to take advantage of American breadths: the capital leakage is considerable.
Young people are tired of war and its ideologies.
They met with the modern world during their exiles in Iran or Pakistan, they appreciated the benefits.
