In the cities, government schools are full of girls and boys.
It will be necessary to provide work for those young people who will no longer want to return to the obscurantism of the old parties or to the corruption of certain leaders.
All, including armed opponents, are mobile phone lovers; television, and its Turkish leaflets presenting a modern world, is followed everywhere.
The army is now present.
Will the authorities that will order it be considered legitimate?
Former commanders of the anti-Soviet struggle are already concerned about reconstructing provincial militias, which will escape central power.
Afghanistan, a mountainous country with strong local identities, should be able to benefit from some decentralization, like Western nations, but the United States wanted to transform it into a centralized state, with strong presidential power, removing the post of prime minister that existed since the 1964 Constitution.
President Karzai does not want foreign controls, especially on the occasion of the elections scheduled for April 2014.
The country has been dependent on foreign aid since the 1950s.
No industry has been restarted, no dam is in good condition, no major irrigation system is repaired.
Everything is imported; nothing is produced except fruit and vegetables.
Priority is given to private initiative.
In a country ruined by thirty years of war, government control over infrastructure would have been necessary.
The rumor was widespread that Afghanistan possessed immense mining wealth.
This only added to the feeling that the Westerners were there only to seize it.
Without energy to process the iron or copper ore on site, nor means of transport to export it through the mountains, there is no mining.
The Chinese have already almost left the Mes Aynak copper mine, leaving international archaeologists (funded by the World Bank) to excavate the immense Buddhist site and remain the province’s most important employers.
It will also take a day for Afghanistan and Pakistan, which are largely dependent on imports and exports, to restore normal relations.
The departure of the French combat troops ended on November 20.
The new cooperation treaty provides for the continuation of traditional aid: high school for girls, boys, department of French at the university, French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support to the Archaeological Delegation.
Since 2009, in an attempt to "win hearts and minds" and realize the impossible task of coinciding aid and offensive actions, a service of "civil-military actions" of the Ministry of Defense (Cimic), abolished in 2012, has led, and carried out by a small French NGO, numerous collective interest works and agricultural rehabilitation actions in dozens of mountain villages.
These works, feeding on local labor, were able to help contain the insurrection: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increased cultivable surfaces.
What will we leave as a memory after two billion euros of military spending?
A much more modest budget would contribute to the improvement of local living conditions, which are very harsh in these valleys often located at over 2,000 meters.
The embassy has received dozens of written requests from small agricultural achievements from local communities in Kapisa province.
In order for them to free themselves from the insurrection led by foreign groups, which the farmers have told me to wish for, it would be necessary to maintain in their favor a small civilian aid, well controlled and that affects them directly.
A forceps constitution in Egypt
This is a new poker blow by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, he has decided to play his vaut.
Taking everyone short, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state gave the assembly two more months to finish its work.
In the past two years, Egypt has been relying on a provisional text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal fraud.
This new initiative has only increased the gap in the country.
For his opponents, the President persists in his “autocratic deliberation”, continuing to “betray his word” and “strike the right.”
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their plan to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy as protests rage across the country.
Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote in favour, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Moreover, this recourse to a rushed vote is the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I retain full powers," these should supposedly end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this constituent assembly, with a vast majority of Islamists, voted on the text yesterday.
The majority of liberals failed to appeal.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had knocked the door, believing they could not make their views known.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities or civil society had done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, substitutes, were added to the rush yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, it is most often unanimously that the articles were voted.
Some commentators were also amused by the fact that one of the only divergences of the day was expressed around... the time of prayer, some members of the committee believing that the pendulum of the constituent was poorly arranged.
The text, which was still being voted last night, contains 234 articles.
Subject to all attention, Article 2 ultimately remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that “the principles of Sharia are the primary source of law.”
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major claim, hoped to replace "principles" with "rules", which would have allowed a stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and their respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrisy,” answer the liberals, who see it only as a communication blow.
Because, according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
According to article 220, Al-Azhar University has a consultative role, in checking compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because “the people called to speak out are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the origins of a theocracy there."
Liberal fears are also fuelled by the fact that the next rector of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system" tempers Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be ambiguity around article 220, because the terms used borrow from religious vocabulary.
There is a reference to “fiqh” in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question may arise in the future is to what extent civil judges are competent to decide on it.”
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is heavily criticized because of the extensive powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another controversial point: the powers conferred on the army.
According to the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Neither will the trials of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as human rights groups have called for.
They also express their concerns about the text, which they consider liberticide.
The crime of blasphemy isined and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences on freedom of expression, of the press.
Moreover, no articles are echoing the protection of women anymore, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This was not mentioned in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak last night on television, protests are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the Center of the World and a sea of salt await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and wild nature.
Argoumenty i Fakty has listed five great reasons to go to Israel.
Go and worship the holy places
The most important place to visit is the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who enters these “baptisms” will be touched by divine grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of Jesus’ miracles: where the water was turned into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he calmed the storm, or where fishing was miraculous.
This is the place where Jesus appeared to His disciples after His resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places, it is in Jerusalem.
Believers walk there on the Rue de la Souffrance or the Way of the Cross (in Latin: the Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the fortress of Antonia (the praetorium), where the trial took place, then leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on the Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Stone of the Unction and the burial.
This is where the Christian center of the world, the symbol of the salvation of humanity, is located.
According to the Christian legend, the Cross Monastery is erected in the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem also houses the most sacred place of the Jews: the Wall of Lamentation, which constitutes the remnant of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave small words accompanied by prayers that are then answered.
Travel in Height
Visit the ruins of Massada Fortress, an ancient refuge from enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins are found on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only alpine lovers can get there by their own means.
For others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m above sea level, there is the ski resort of Mont Hermont which welcomes many tourists in winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski trails are a total of 45 km long.
Ancient beliefs suggest that pagan gods once lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
The country has about 300 museums.
It is not possible to visit them all in one visit.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth a visit.
First: the Museum of Israel located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the very ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea manuscripts, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
Also see: Tel Aviv Art Museum.
It exhibits mainly the paintings of the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of moldings from visitors and guards of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the only private Ralli Museum where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Entrance is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which goes back on the most dramatic historical pages of history.
The most tragic part is the Children’s Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter into total darkness.
The stars are shining.
Then you hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
The three major resorts of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in the winter, as the water temperature does not fall below 21 degrees while the air temperature can reach 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point on Earth, or 417 m below sea level.
The blue-colored water contains saliva and very easily holds back swimmers, even those who do not know how to swim.
The surrounding landscapes are of surreal beauty.
We come there to perform a treatment based on saltwater, lemon, curative mud and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the Secrets of Antiquity
They are guarded by the old town of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the shore of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is traversed by the famous Via Maris that connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it is here that Noah built his ark and that Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists especially like to walk through the narrow streets that carry the name of the zodiac signs.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile to you.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds who come to take photos from all over Israel and even from other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman theatre, "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer dollars to euros, as they are easily exchanged for shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
As for urban transport, these are mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only subway line in the country, consisting of six stations and capable of connecting the lower and upper parts of the city.
It is almost an underground funicular.
The trip in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition is to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport cessate.
The working week begins on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve only casher food, which excludes pork, seafood, unskalled fish and dishes made up of both milk and meat.
There are a multitude of meals from lamb and beef, soups and desserts from coconut milk, but also humus, traditional Jewish paste, various sauces, peach balls, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no wandering dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are a lot of well-fed cats that walk in the high air.
You can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars at night.
These puppies love passing places and do not refuse to be given them.
The rental price of a car varies from $37 for 24 hours (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
An entrance to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The language of numbers
Three million tourists from around the world visited Israel in 2012.
These were mostly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 miles of Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, which is 51% more than in 2010, before the visa cancellation on February 9, 2011.
"Who has a language, to Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
As MPs and human rights activists debate what the mandatory language test law will give, fraudsters selling “fake” certificates have already made their appearance in the country.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, these are nationals of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to earn money to help their families stay at home.
Since December 1, a law has entered into force and stipulates that every migrant worker must pass a Russian language exam.
For now, this rule only applies to those who intend to work in the services, housing, private services and retail sectors.
However, over time, the Federal Migration Service promises, tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, knowledge of the language, but also of the history of Russia and the legal foundations will be validated.
You will need to validate your knowledge of the Russian language to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has the status of official language are exempt.
Persons who obtained education certificates or diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centers will be under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, the University of Friendship of Peoples, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to pass the exams in all cities in the country: more than 160 centres have already been opened across the territory.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by MEPs from the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders have already repeatedly asked the question in the press: what will it bring?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First, respond representatives of the migration service, this will reduce the number of people suffering from "slavery at work".
Many talk about defending the rights of migrant workers, explains the director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
The problems arise for immigrants without profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "travel" in a crowded house where he and dozens of his peers will torment for months without food and paper and will have to trim between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive a lot of complaints from our immigrants.
"At home, they are promised one thing, and when they arrive, they are deceived, their passports are taken, and they do not get the planned salary," said Tolib Charipov, Head of the Directorate of Migration Services for the work of the Tajikistan Migration Service.
Do not argue with me, sir.
However, many citizens of Central Asian republics who want to come to make money in Russia are confident that they not only know the language of the country they want to go to, but also write with difficulty in their own language.
This is of course not their fault, but their misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbek, and Tajik can afford to attend even a suitable primary education.
In fact, their families don’t even have anything to feed their children, not to mention dressing them properly and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people go out to earn money as soon as the opportunity comes.
It’s hard when you don’t know the language.
“You feel diminished and diminished.”
Human rights defenders note, however, an important aspect of the language law.
The examinations will only be for migrants who have legal status.
Without status, there will be no subsequent examination or official work.
Nevertheless, most migrant workers continue to live illegally in Russia.
“Welcome or Defense to Enter”
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to get an official status in Russia.
The administrative barriers and always these language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 thousand rubles.
And then you can get a fake registration quickly for only 1500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have fake documents, that we have no records, hence the cases of extortion.
"They are asking us for 100, 200 rubles, what to buy cigarettes, tea," said Oumed Khouchkadamov, a citizen of Tajikistan.
Hurry up, don’t be upset and buy yourself a beautiful work of art.
From the first day of the language law’s entry into force, it was discovered that migrants’ registration papers were not the only ones to be fake.
Several false language exam certificates have already been confiscated by federal immigration officials.
The counterfeit paper comes out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not have them for nothing: every migrant who hoped to facilitate the task of examinations had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
It is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Representatives of power and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these “papers.”
Authorities may give migrant workers who have not been able to validate the first test time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered a job in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of Internal Affairs does not deal with the arms market.
The proportion of crimes involving legal weapons is very low.
The Russian Interior Ministry has proposed tougher laws against civilian weapons carriers.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: whether it is the shootings carried out during weddings or the killing organized by the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, who killed seven people.
The police want to ban the use of rubber bullet guns in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining a gun permit from 18 to 21 years.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the weapons law would be introduced to the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is pleased to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "pushing the screw."
An open letter appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demanded to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, Vasily Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC, told the Russian service.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, over a six-month period in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded in the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that tightening civil weapons laws will not prevent criminals from sourcing from the black market.
According to them, any weapon can be found in Moscow today at a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior says it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black market of weapons is supplied through several channels.
The main channels are five, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served ten years in the Ministry of Education and the Headquarters.
Screenshot of a site taking weapons orders
The first is "military trace", that is, weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by Caucasians," Baranets said.
The second type of weapons from the black market are those stolen by criminals from law enforcement.
Baranets explained that these are both weapons stolen from police stocks and those stolen directly from law enforcement representatives.
Illegal guns are sold from military warehouses.
Many of them often suffered explosions.
"Attested versions indicate that some fires were deliberately triggered to hide the deficit," the former military said.
For Baranets, weapons manufacturers are there for something.
"We see private weapons factories that do not compete with competition in the international market and sell weapons on the black market, in Moscow," one expert said.
Another source of the black market is smuggling.
A significant proportion of guns and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a local production, sometimes handicraft, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply," adds the former military.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on the issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, criminal records and public data from weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, come from the army and law enforcement.
Half of the weapons present on the black market were found there "because of the employees whose work is related to weapons," the report explains.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from places of military conflict, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% come from “clandestine sheets”.
A salesman and consultant at an armor store who asked to remain anonymous assured that for a long time no one has bought the weapons found by these clandestine excavators; they are too old.
Most often, according to him, sellers will look for new goods in military warehouses.
The person purchases through a sign a unit, for example, a TT pistol.
It is delivered by passing the goods through a grillage.
“He transports it to the city and sells it for €900 per unit with two chargers,” he says.
"It is true that the police are aware of all the affairs, so when crimes are about to be clarified, they make a check purchase from illegal arms dealers," the seller added.
Like in a luxury store.
The seller and buyer usually find themselves through knowledge.
I consulted sites, blogs, until a guy showed up and offered me to come to the Begovaya station where someone would take me into a "point" to shop.
The price of the gun was given to me.
Victor Baranets as military observer
To find a gun, I need to know someone who has a contact, explains the seller.
There are sellers on the markets, but there you also have to come by saying, for example, "From such a person, who asked me to transmit that his daughter lost a tooth."
Now I even buy a pair of American fists with the help of someone I trust.
He gives them to me only because he knows that I will not give them to him.
New kids are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former military officer Victor Baranets tried himself as an illegal arms buyer in the mid-1990s when he was preparing to publish an article on the subject.
The schemes, he said, have not changed.
He was given a photo album in which was "everything you want."
“I thought I was in a luxury shop,” the military remembers.
There is no secret for the buyer, Baranets explains, you can try everything.
As a potential customer, I don’t just buy, we go with the seller into the forest and install a target.
“They let me shoot and when I’m convinced the weapon works well, we start negotiating,” the expert describes.
A shop from the couch
Search engines show sites and groups on Vkontakte where weapons can be purchased "for different uses".
You do not need any documents or anyone to meet.
"It's enough to have a precise sum of money," it is written in the advertisement on the site "Buy a gun or a combat machine gun".
Users leave their requests and ask questions.
Will it be sold to minors?
"Without permission, of course," asks the user "Ivan" (reserved spelling).
"Buy TT. Moscow," writes "Fedorenkov" in his very direct request.
The Federal Security Service has spread an enormous network of fake sites and is hoarding people willing to buy combat weapons.
People rush on food like hungry wolves and then they find themselves mining coal in Siberia
Victor Baranets, observer and former military officer
I have heard about this type of schemes: generally, the site is registered outside the scope of Russian laws.
People are taking orders.
