The input of information has been improved (the system receives more data), but the performance, for now, is not really.
We’re trying to change that and we’re working on truly 3D imaging systems that run on different technologies, including projection technologies.
We need to bring the computer world into our own, into the physical world, to make it more tactile.
For this, however, it is necessary to identify not only the user, but also the space that surrounds him.
Thus, we will be able to complement the real world with virtual objects in a more convenient form.
Let’s get rid of these stupid virtual reality headsets!
What do you think of the voice command?
It is appreciated, but is it not overestimated?
It cannot be said that this is the panacea: the question of confidentiality arises because one does not always want to inform others of his actions or intentions.
In fact, every type of interaction with the computer is good, but each in its niche.
For example, to order the devices in public places, we had a project for which we thought of gestures, not widespread gestures, but rather discreet, restricted gestures.
The gestures were not captured by the camera of the device, but by a bracelet worn in the hand that recorded the movements of bones and muscles.
It is currently large, but it is theoretically possible to reduce it to the size of a watch.
In fact, the future will be marked by the mixed command, for example: gesture + voice.
That is to say?
For example, how would you ask me to pass this can to you?
You would do it with words and gestures.
Usually I just talk.
It will be hard to recognize.
So, do you want to force users to adjust based on what the machine can or can’t do at a given time?
Not necessarily, but it is a relationship.
I think very soon we will have to work on developing new types of sensors that will allow us to better identify human reactions.
This can be, for example, laser sensors, they produce a fairly good depth resolution and this is very important.
If you are interested in your work on Xbox Kinect sensors, what do you dislike about modern cameras?
Are they lacking in resolution, depth or something else?
In principle, it is on the current generation that we rely in our work on 3D recognition.
It would obviously be good to get about 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 cps.
But the problem is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and depth.
Compared to the latter, all current technologies are pretty good, which adds work to algorithm designers.
The resolution according to the axes X and Y, but also Z, must be kept in mind.
The speed also matters a lot, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and 30 c/s is really not enough, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche from our Redmond laboratory has given the touch of sensors a regular processing delay of between 1 and 100 μs, with current sensors closer to the second value (60-100).
