For now, one of the interesting techniques is the use of second hand to serve as an image medium.
It perfectly copes with the pressure.
But there are also technologies that are actually intended to attribute palpability to these "images in the air": for example, the interference of several ultrasound rays directed to a specific point where the finger is located and which gives you the feeling, for the moment still weak, of a breath of air on the ends of the fingers.
There are also bracelets worn on the wrists that affect the nerve endings of the fingers, they are also a work axis with perspectives.
Have you tried to fool your brain?
Make him believe he feels what he should normally feel when he sees something?
This is a good idea, I haven’t tried it yet.
There’s still one task down there that you’ll still have to work on for a long time: how to make someone who’s physically in a very small space believe he’s walking in an almost infinite open space – we’re working on running carpets concepts (nothing to do with those we find in fitness clubs), mobile platforms and also giant balls.
