The head of the ISC (Supreme Institution for Public Finance Control) said: “The control of the pseudo-independent work (in Czech “Švarc system”) has failed because of politicians.
In the field of public procurement, the Czech Republic has competent inspectors and quality legislation but is lagging behind in its implementation.
This was stated by Miloslav Kala, vice president of the Higher Institution for Public Finance Control, in an interview with Aktuálně.cz.
"The law will never be perfect, but its application must be fair and, in my opinion, that's what is lacking in us," Kala said in his comment on the current situation.
A joint inspection conducted by Czech and German inspectors also suggests similar conclusions.
He cites as an example of abuse the approach of the “Švarc system” by Petr Nečas.
Mr. Prime Minister recently stated that the SDG would not bother entrepreneurs with checks; is it permitted or prohibited?
"The law must be applied in one way or another, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government can not prevent an authority responsible for going to inspect from demanding compliance with the law," says Kala.
During the meeting of the Audit Committee in the House of Deputies, you talked about a Czech-German project in which the public procurement legislation of these two countries was compared.
What was it specifically about?
This is a parallel control that we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, EU legislation provides for how to manage public procurement and specific national laws and practices follow it.
We have put together all this and although this control procedure is not yet completed, very interesting differences have appeared to us: generally speaking, our legislation may be "stricter and better quality", however, according to some parameters, the practice as such is better in Germany.
This confirms, therefore, that it is not enough to continuously develop increasingly detailed rules, but that it is necessary to focus on the implementation of the law itself.
How can this project actually help you and what does it mean for you?
A common control of this type should just help us stop trying to clarify laws, lower and improve thresholds, when this does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means obtaining the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But by lowering market thresholds, this goal will not necessarily be achieved.
It may be that this system is so overwhelmed by paperwork that those who search for its gaps will find much more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You talk about internal issues related to the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there a similar institution to our ISC or a different way of organizing?
As for institutions, similar to the ISC, there works the Bundesrechnungshof which is organized similarly, it also has a council constituted slightly differently, but these two institutions proceed fundamentally in a similar way.
The competences are also, to some extent, similar, but with a nuance compared to our system: as Germany is a federal structure, it therefore also has accounts of this type at the level of the different Länder.
The BRH can only control the federal money, which in our country corresponds to the state resources.
Public funds managed by the regions and municipalities are controlled there at the level of the council of the Länder.
Is national legislation easier than ours?
I would not like to make a general comparison without concrete data, however, in some areas, Germany is often designated as a model but one can not say that it does better in all areas.
Maybe it’s because they have better inspectors?
No, not, but I repeat, I do not have comparison data.
However, it must also be said that this country that we see as a model also faces a whole host of problems.
Otherwise they would have no advantage of cooperating with our institution, right?
With regard to national legislation, what has the amendment of the Public Procurement Act meant for you as an institution, are its effects already being felt?
Since this amendment came into force relatively recently, it has no impact on our control operations yet.
As we do controls a posteriori, we have to count on a certain delay.
Our observations concern only, for the time being, the process of preparing for future checks – we have launched a new “risk detection of mismanagement” tool with which we spotted 14,000 public contracts – there these changes will of course be felt, because the thresholds have been modified as well as the conditions of certain types of tender procedures and so on.
Do you consider the adoption of this law to be an advantage or an additional burden for the administration?
I think this law is a step in the right direction and I hope the future will confirm it.
The problem that may arise is that these rules become more stringent and it is not possible to comply with them.
Already under the regime of the previous regulation, the provider (e.g. the regional council, in the case of regional operational programmes) forced the subjects controlled to accept that any violation of the market law means a breach of budgetary discipline.
So is it really worth making the law stricter this way?
Not in this way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or abuse the system but not punish those who make formal mistakes without consequences on the decision-making process.
Such a system will put pressure on the administration.
So what is the solution to get out of it?
Let’s look where we are not going.
Recently, the prime minister said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with checks on the so-called Švarc system - what does this mean?
Is the Švarc system prohibited or permitted?
The law must be enforced in one way or another, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government cannot prevent an authority from acting to go inspect and demand compliance with the law.
He may declare, “We will change the law and allow it,” but he cannot say that we will act as if nothing happened.
The law on contracts contains relatively strict rules on the formalities to be fulfilled, precisely in order to protect the tender.
But it is also tragic that an bidder is eliminated only because of formal defects.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be fair and that is, in my opinion, what we lack.
