Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of this agency, it is the second member state of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started a close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and in the years that followed participated in a number of ESA projects.
However, Poland’s journey to space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, passionate Poles worked on space flights; they did not always encounter understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, A. Šternfeld’s lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas drawn from his cutting-edge work entitled “Introduction to Astronautics”.
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the listeners cold and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld received in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his book "Introduction to Astronautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote numerous books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of world-renowned astronautics, his contribution was rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the hidden side of the Moon.
As early as 1925 a drainage was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or brake drainage.
The only information known about this drainage is that of the press of the time.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It is clear from the conserved documents that this research had reached the experimental stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search was interrupted.
In 1937, plans for a photoelectric fighter rocket, drawn by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects aimed at the military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were conducted by the provisional advisory scientific committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works devoted to aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, a company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the newspaper Problème, in which there are four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
In early 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and in the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1,800 meters was 80 cm long and weighed just under 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version, RM-1A, was built, and during the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-story RM-2 rocket were started in the Bledov desert.
This rocket was 1.4 meters long and weighed probably 11.5 kilograms.
The next prototype should have been able to perform concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965 succeeded the first RM rocket.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A had a space offering a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of vehicles was 37 km.
In the period 1965-1968, Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful load of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
Poland joined the Committee for Space Research (COSPAR) in 1960 and a national committee was established two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
