The movie Argo: When Everything Goes Worse, Call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a group of Islamist students stormed the U.S. embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had supported his regime for decades.
The situation did not offer the US administration a positive outcome, it could not, indeed, abandon the Shah, because it would have severely shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of the hostages.
It was a tough blow to the prestige of the United States, further aggravated later by the fiasco of the attempt to release hostages by force.
The kidnapped diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iran sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian defeat contributed heavily to the defeat of Jimmy Carter over Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, directed by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory to America.
Just before it was occupied, six employees escaped the embassy.
After complicated journeys, they found themselves in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran through a rocambolesque cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a filming team that came to make signs for the shooting of a major science fiction film.
Combination of Genres
The plan by exfiltration expert Tony Mendez requires the collaboration of Hollywood.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized stores this film project, press conferences were held and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, with the film based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck’s film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is a part of a realistically conceived political thriller but also a “caper movie”, the story of a successful blow, a betrayal – like, for example, in the Ocean’s trilogy eleven, twelve and thirteen.
The atmospheres succeed: documentary-style Tehran sequences (in the subtitled sequences iconic photographs of the time of events are presented and the way in which, thanks to these photos, these same situations were transcribed into the film, there are no big differences),
lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the hallways and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has started his career again.
From a ridiculous actor, he became a respected director and his play as an actor ceased to arouse ironic remarks.
Argo is her third feature film after the dark policeman "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
This is also Affleck’s first film not to take place in his home town, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed his first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of the atmosphere in Argo where Tehran’s role “is held” by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive by its clarity which also suggests the confusion and unpredictability that occurs when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his colleagues get a similar effect in fictional scenes (the fake shooting team in Tehran's bazar).
Too much action in too many places.
The director had to be content with a subject that in fact offers only a few exciting scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
It does well, it sometimes adds some elements to reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is dismissed by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the landing track is quite pulled by the hair).
The weakness of Argo lies in its dissipation, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their roles of Hollywood co-workers, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are not, far from being the only ones in this case.
Affleck’s film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, it is seen with moderate interest, appreciating the 1970s realisation and retro style.
He trains the spectator, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a history still, in a way, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the representation of the secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the affair.
Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and the circus
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually conducts a public survey on the most absurd banking fees, has now decided to launch the contest of the regulation or ideas from the "EU workshop" the most absurd.
"The fact that the EU has recently considered adopting a 40 percent quota of women for the management of major European companies has been at the origin of our decision," said Patrik Nacher, the organizer of the survey.
Among the absurdities mentioned, there is already, for example, the recent decision of the European Court of Justice to unify insurance premiums for men and women.
Until now, however, women were preferred in terms of life insurance rates because they represent, objectively, a lower risk for insurance companies.
People can report until the end of the year any other such incredible idea of the "EU workshop".
"The vote will take place before the end of February 2013," Nacher said.
Among the controversial EU regulations are, for example, the obligation to add biocomponents to fuels, which has harmful consequences for the environment, or the prohibition to use reliable mercury thermometers, only because they contain a relatively small amount of a dangerous substance, or the directive on the size of chicken cages, which has resulted in an increase in the price of eggs.
Criticisms have also been raised in the past against the de facto ban on the use of the phrase "butter to tart" or the withdrawal from the sale of traditional bulbs.
Quality bananas should be 14 centimeters in size.
The European administration often reacts under the pressure of a commercial or industrial lobby whose demands are usually defended in Brussels by a state or a group of states (so the Czech Republic currently imposes the demands of its banks by threatening to use its veto right).
The interests of pressure groups are also, for example, at the root of the fact that in the EU bananas must not be less than 14 cm in size or have an "abnormal curvature".
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it merely harmonised non-homogeneous national standards that complicated trade.
Standards on fruits and vegetables have been eased despite opposition from some states, claiming that existing directives lead to food waste.
The first prize may be awarded in this survey to last year’s EU regulation that must include a warning on inflatable balloons that children under the age of 8 should not inflate without adult supervision.
The EU has referred to a U.S. survey that shows that balloons are, among toys, the leading cause of child death from suffocation.
A similar restriction applies to children under the age of 14 when it comes to blowing in trade fair trumpets.
We also have strange ideas.
The following rule concerning the European officials themselves is quite absurd: due to the sensitivity of this topic to Greece, anyone with an official position within the EU can not use the name "Macedonia" and must, instead, speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In collaboration with the association "Laissez Faire" of liberal economists, the server Bankovnípoplatky.com named in this investigation, in addition to some of the absurdities mentioned above, the EU regulation on the volume of food stockpiles on the territory of the Czech Republic.
The EU had set maximum volumes for food stocks that could be on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the volumes fixed for canned mushrooms and therefore risked a heavy fine.
The organizers of this survey found interesting the idea of paying money to certain countries because they do not have access to the sea and the idea of granting a subsidy to apply for subsidies.
These ideas, however, do not come from Brussels but from Prague.
“The fact that we don’t have the sea is a disadvantage.
We are going to ask the European Union for a refund."This was stated in the autumn of 2004 by the then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD).
He argued that, due to our wheat production, and following the so-called "interventionist" purchases, the state had found itself with full stocks that it had to export.
According to Palas, the EU should have paid us millions of euros, because the Czech Republic is far from ports.
Eventually, the European Commission responded positively to the Czech demand and organized a tender for the purchase of wheat from countries without maritime access.
The subsidies for obtaining subsidies were proposed to the municipalities by the Ministry of Local Development headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), which were to be used in writing applications for subsidies granted by Brussels.
The EU says: “Strange regulations are rare.”
While regulations are often critical in Member States, according to many experts, the EU’s efforts in regulating and improving the effectiveness of the EU’s functioning as well as in the area of its overall development deserve rather praise.
More serious is, for example, according to experts, the problem of using EU grants for projects that have absolutely nothing to do with the strengthening of European integration, but were imposed by Member States in budget negotiations.
The fact that the Czech Republic, like other EU countries, must fight in Brussels for the right to use specific names for these traditional products (which it does not always win) arouses vivid emotions among the Czechs.
If after six years of battle against the Germans and the Austrians, the Czechs successfully defended the name "Olomoucké tvarůžky", for the name "Tuzemský rum" which dates back to the 19th century, our producers had to replace it with the name "Tuzemák".
Only products made from sugar cane alcohol, and not from beet sugar, may be referred to as rum.
The official list of registered products in the EU now includes world-renowned cheeses such as Feta or Gorgonzola, Lübeck and Parma jambon, Karlovy Vary (Karlovarské suchary), Pohořelice and Třeboň (Pohořelický a Třeboňský kapr) and Žatec (Žatecký chmel).
Pardubice spice bread ("Pardubický perník") and the cakes called "Cornets de Hořice" ("hořické trubičky") can also be proud of their community brand.
