The architects of the MVRDV office prove that real adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To convince yourself, just look at Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I find this building funny, it's very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passing woman on the street's bottom.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a big neighboring company, tells us, “Yes, this building is really beautiful.”
I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has an Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Nowadays, no one is willing to go to one of these lingering libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town that has nothing attractive at the gates of Rotterdam, holds a very special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls displays the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to give some neurons back to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and reproduce the seven fictional bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of beautiful little miniatures of painted armed concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to regain control of statistics: building a library!
Winy Maas, from the Rotterdam architectural office MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of mindful and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual sputum and presented himself to the contest in 2003 with five pounds under his arm and a scratch on his face.
And while the members of the jury were still staring at each other, confused and lifting up their shoulders, Maas, the overwhelmed, stacked his books of choice in order of size to make it a pyramid, and ended his activist-backed speech with one: "Dear Common!"
Here is my proposal for the Spijkenisse Book Mountain, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain of 30 million euros sprang from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and townhouses for a total of 50 homes.
In early November, the Book Mountain received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus this dull little town, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and a town hall of an awful ugliness, whose white façades invite to think that they are home to a dairy, has enriched itself with a contemporary architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under the cheese bell.
Sure, an elevator takes you to the heart of the massive, but the real joys of reading and architecture open up to you as you tread the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The entirely glass interior is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and the elegant reverberals speak unambiguously the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking at public banks, dogs and little boys and girls playing with the ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally, the library rays are located along the façade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal,” explains Willy Maas.
We completely overturned the classic spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books has been skillfully arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the building's technical center.
A special beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes lambris, sometimes balustrades, sometimes staircase ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened building architects and engineers do not want unknown materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to Standard.
This is how one day we found in a frison farm an ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, a millimetre thick synthetic membrane has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It is cheap and saves time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be thrown away.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates of a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes colour and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 meters, the literary café offers a stunning view of the city, as well as Dutch croquettes and pot ficus.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute toining the ideal level of moisture of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the New Soul
“It’s incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal.
Although the mountain of books lies beneath a glass bell, the sun only shines the interior for a short time, even on days of good weather.
The thick wooden bars mounted across the glass facade serve as a sunshine, intercepting much of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
Completely automated stores take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was also there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse’s “soul finally found.”
A few weeks ago, each citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure helped to fill the gaps in the library that was not yet fully enclosed (now it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays flood from everywhere.
For architect Winy Maas, “There is nothing worse than a half-empty library.”
“I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
It’s just for decoration.”
This is how MVRDV has reached the master discipline called, in professional jargon, “creation of an identity.”
Spijkenisse has written a new page of literary history.
She may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, this is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: “The Germans need to play a bigger role.”
Germany voted to abstain from voting on the admission of a Palestinian state.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian request for observer status at the United Nations.
He then chose to abstain.
Why is ?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not endorse what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as itins special relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support the American position.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but was not too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 insurgency in Libya, Germany also chose to abstain in the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
Eventually, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany find it difficult to take a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so-called defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
In addition, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans fought on several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still struggling to find this role, but are on the way to a “more normal” foreign policy.
Foreign policy, such as in France or Britain
So what does the term “normal” foreign policy really mean for the Germans?
It demonstrates the willingness to take positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including on national matters.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, thus by its exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of other great powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Did these economic interests influence Germany’s stance on the conflict in the Middle East and abstention in the UN vote?
Germany first has important outlets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to strike the public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive element.
However, I would not attach too much importance to it, as it is not a purely unilateral relationship.
But this is, in any case, a decisive element in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany hurt its relations with the United States by choosing to abstain in major votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think Europeans and Americans understand the German position perfectly.
That is why I think the fracture is not as serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Maybe even Germany will be more respected.
In fact, Germany has demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, the views on the Palestinian initiative vary.
The United States, on the other hand, vetoed with a clear voice.
Are there differences between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe the Obama Administration secretly shows a great understanding of the European position.
But given the country’s political configuration, the government of course cannot defend its position publicly.
I think the real differences in opinions are not as big as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from overflowing with enthusiasm for Netanyahu’s policy.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of its major European partners, on the other?
I don’t think it makes things easier for the Germans.
Obviously, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, but today, this is not the case.
They therefore cannot fit within a broader political line and must affirm their singular position.
This is what they are doing now on the euro issue.
In my opinion, Germany will take on the role of a locomotive in the future and push Europe to adopt a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This question has always been delicate.
But I think the Germans are well aware that they must play a role that marks more of their independence.
Is Germany playing a major role on the international stage, does Germany just want to play a key role?
Or is it always difficult to take on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable for her and, for obvious reasons, the country is still struggling to play a larger role.
If one looks at, for example, the euro crisis, one notices that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are being heard.
This does not make things easier for the Germans.
In fact, it’s always the same problem: we don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
She has to deal with very different neighbors and opinions, and that’s not easy.
Today, the U.S. influence on European politics is only diminishing, but at the moment, the EU does not fill that void, so who is left?
The Germans will have to play a bigger role.
And even if they don’t like it, even if it’s unpleasant to them and they’re just less appreciated, it’s life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, DC, an institute where scholars and policy experts from Europe and North America work together to analyze the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Trade Protection" in China: When Puma and Armani Suddenly Become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands worldwide.
Armani Polo, what is it?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but that has nothing to do with the original company.
The trademark thus enjoys such protection that the company that bears its name cannot file a complaint.
And even if she could, it is not certain that she would get gain of cause.
“It’s becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their brands in China,” says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing’s firm specializing in property rights violations in the Far East.
Every week, a new file comes to my office.
Imitators only need a few additional letters to be able to register their brands.
So instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied, such as Puma, the sportswear manufacturer.
Pattloch opens a workbook containing the registrations made with the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the brand Zegna DF Puma, a name that the firm artificially created by appropriating part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a well-known fact that the Chinese have become the world champions of copying and infringing intellectual property.
In major cities, there are multi-storey shopping centers that almost only sell counterfeits.
However, Pattloch’s cases are different: his clients charge him to tackle the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese speak of "Bang Mingpai", a parent brand.
The term is derived from “Bang Dakuan”.
