Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and blennorragia (or gonorrhea).
Common ISTs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
The lice of the pubis and the gall belong to the parasitic ISTs.
Which groups are mainly affected?
Syphilis and blennorragia often appear in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert-Koch Institute estimates that sexual intercourse between men is responsible for at least four out of five cases of syphilis in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia-related infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungal), blennorragia, and human papillomavirus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The spread rate of HIV among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany. However, about 20% of new HIV infections are observed within this group.
In young people, a significantly higher rate of chlamydia-related infections is observed than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people aged 15 to 25.
In addition, in Germany, human papillomavirus is common among young people.
What is the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert-Koch Institute, the number of cases of syphilis has more than doubled in 10 years: the figure increased from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has declined.
In 2011, there were approximately 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one-tenth compared to the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexual illness?
Infectious diseases can cause abscesses in the genital organs, urine pain, white losses, pain in the lower abdomen, as well as the appearance of pimples and warts.
However, they regularly cause no pain or other symptoms and therefore remain hidden.
How to protect?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they do not protect 100%.
The reason for this is that the pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted by lubricating infection or by close body contact.
Therefore, experts recommend that anyone who frequently changes sexual partners regularly undergo examinations.
Most rapidly detected ISTs can be cured and late sequences can be avoided.
