Bradley Manning has not complained about ill-treatment, prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to counter the allegations of abuse that Bradley Manning might have been the victim of during his detention.
The trial is about Manning’s detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants to classify the case on the grounds that Manning’s seizure took place under extremely difficult conditions.
He is accused of stealing thousands of documents.
Prosecutors tried to demonstrate on Friday that soldier Bradley Manning -- accused of being the source of the largest leak of confidential information in the entire history of the U.S. military -- missed numerous occasions to complain of the ill-treatment he claims to have suffered during his military detention.
During a counter-interrogation with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney General Ashden Fein claimed that recordings of weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints about his treatment.
The counter-interrogation — during a hearing, the defense filed a petition demanding that the Manning case be classified on the grounds that the kidnapping took place under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment — took place a day after Manning testified about her desire to commit suicide during her detention.
The military intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were later published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source.
During Friday’s hearing, Fein examined with Manning the forms the officers had filled in after their encounter with Manning, during his detention in Quantico military prison, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein mentioned the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment his guards reserved for him was "excellent" and that the treatment he had received in prison was overall "very professional."
The forms do not state any complaints for ill-treatment, although officers have directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he orally expressed concerns about certain issues and that visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not record the issues mentioned.
"They wrote 'no problem' (after addressing concerns), and yet that didn't mean I didn't raise problems," Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during an interview in January 2011 with the special committee that had gathered to discuss suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during the meeting was to change his restrictive status indicating a “risk of injury.”
The military said they had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for his own protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was fine, and I wanted to be removed from that status... so that I could enjoy a better quality of life from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for two months before being transferred to the military prison from the Marine Corps base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he planned to commit suicide while in Kuwait and once fainted due to the heat.
He added that not being kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very anxious.
"My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage," Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Once at Quantico, Manning said he had spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without companionship.
Manning also added that the only objects he had were a mattress, a blanket, tongs, clothes and his glasses.
He tried to stay in motion because sleeping or lying down during the day was contrary to the regulation.
Manning also specified that when he was trying to fall asleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards could not see his face when he turned around at night, they woke him up so that he could see his face.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint over Manning’s treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation in his Thursday testimony — that after being forced to sleep naked a night in his cell at Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other detainees one morning, during the call.
Manning testified that at no time was she allowed to cover herself with a blanket during the call.
During the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he had deduced from his guard's order that he should let go of his blanket that could have hidden his nakedness, but he admitted that no one had ordered him to let go.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because he had tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning would have told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his slip or tongs to injure himself, but he had not.
That night, Manning testified that her underwear, tongs, and glasses had been removed from her cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account the experiences he experienced during his detention and that he will considerably reduce his sentence if he is to be found guilty in a martial court, a trial that is expected to take place early next year.
The defense said Manning plans to plead guilty for the least serious crimes and to fight for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors arguing that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has confirmed that Manning was imprisoned in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees at Quantico.
The charges against Manning include the theft of public assets or documents, collusion with the enemy, leading to the unlawful publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of national defense-related information.
If all the accusers are detained, he receives life imprisonment.
