After scrolling through numerous publications and submitting the idea to a discussion group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and colleagues defined boredom as an experience that consists of “wishing to do something but failing to get into a satisfactory activity.”
What differentiates boredom from apathy, he says, is that the person is not undertaking a task though he would like to.
With apathy, he says, there is no desire to do anything.
What is at the heart of boredom, he said, is “the interruption of the process of attention, associated with a bad mood and the feeling that time goes slowly.”
Depression can be very similar to depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that if both can be linked, people who get bored tend to think that the problem comes from the environment or the world, while depressed people think that the problem comes from them.
Sometimes we think we’re boring when it’s actually a concentration problem.
As part of their study, “The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention,” which was published in the journal “Perspectives on Psychological Science” in September, Professor Eastwood and colleagues highlighted an earlier experiment in which participants listened to on cassette, the voice of a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups heard, from the next room, the too loud sound of a TV show that had no connection, others just heard the TV show, and the third group did not hear the soundtrack at all.
Those who heard TV at a low noise level said they were more annoyed than the other two groups – they had trouble concentrating, but didn’t know why, and attributed this concentration problem to boredom.
When you’re trying to focus on a difficult or disturbing task, a break from attention can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study’s authors.
On the other hand, when you do a boring task, "like watching objects on a editing chain, music can help you not get bored."
In fact, he says, now we know that when you torture yourself or chew yourself, these gestures, often seen as signs of boredom, are actually a good way to stay physically alert.
“Studies have shown that children who are allowed to gigot learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to stay unmoving,” Professor Fenske said.
We all get bored one day or another - the delay of my plane flight, a speaker with a monocorde voice, a boring movie.
But some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To measure this, researchers developed a “Predisposition Scale to Boredom” in the 1980s.
The scale includes statements such as, “Among the tasks I do, many of them are repetitive and monotonous,” and “I have so many interests that I don’t have time to do everything.”
Using such a scale, the researchers found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, and in particular need numerous and varied stimuli.
In general, teenagers are rapidly overwhelmed.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of individual and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment during which he contacted 400 teens and their parents seven to eight times a day via a beeper.
He found that 32 percent of teenagers getting bored at school and during their homework, while 23 percent getting bored when they were not at school.
In contrast, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the percentages of boredom today, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
