For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through the steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by carrying sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It has to work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphur gas emanating from the earth's intestines solidifies in contact with the air.
After harvesting large sulfur rocks, weighing a total of 70 kilograms, he placed them in two bamboo baskets that he loaded on his shoulders through the steep paths.
There are only 250 meters to the summit of the volcano that culminates at 2,386 meters of altitude, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb that distance, in a turtle-like shape, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost them their lives, as it happened to a French tourist who fell deadly into the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilogram of sulfur extracted.
Once on the top, there is a path between tourists who photograph them as if they were circus beasts, and wearyly carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers to the scale that a mining company installed a little below at 1,850 meters of altitude.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, we can say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents of euro) per kilogram of sulfur.
She then sells it to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) as this mineral is very present in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even used to whiten sugar.
“As we carry about 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip,” says Anto, who generally makes three trips a day.
Each takes him 3 hours and he ends up exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11,50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although this seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it’s three times what it would earn in the fields.
"The miners' income is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1,20 euros) per day and where the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros)," says the carrier who once worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, her salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) a day and the job wasn’t that hard, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as sulfur: “I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindu, and I brought her back to Java for her to convert to Islam.”
Anto suffers from asthma, breathing with difficulty, coughing constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At age 27, he spent three of his life challenging danger on the Kawah ljen, but sulfur has already begun to make him pay the bill even though he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
