UNASUR summit ends without the Lima Declaration being made public
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the seven delegates present.
Efe has repeatedly attempted access to the document signed at the Sixth Ordinary Meeting of UNASUR Heads of State and Government, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially that it would be disclosed after the summit closed, then said it would be published from time to time on the Peruvian government’s website.
When asked about the text, they that its content had been exposed by Peruvian President Ollante Humala in brief press releases.
Journalists' access to information about the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the no-sound video of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information circulating among the journalists was that given by press officials from some of the Unasur governments who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document disclosed during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media that demanded more important information.
Later, the Peruvian presidency sent an email to the media with the "final statement" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru was the host of the 3rd South American-Arab Summit (ASPA) and, on this occasion, although it was requested with instance by the press, it did not broadcast the statement also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official website of the ASPA, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities attempted to set up secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the collection of information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court settling a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICC’s decision to hear the advocates of both sides in the trial that Lima filed against Santiago, which begins Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes we have today before this international court," said President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international tribunals,” said President Piñera, giving a handshake to President Humala, alongside the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by the two presidents that they would submit to the ICC came after Colombia this week denounced the Bogotá Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of this international tribunal, following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua that it considered seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the removal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was tasked with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The delegate read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action of 31 projects had been set between the South American countries for a total of $17 million of investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the Unasur countries would put in place “important steps to the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits.”
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions for better access to medicines, cheap internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters."
With a Europe in crisis, “economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphal matrix but must help increase our productive matrix and see a better future for our peoples,” concluded President Humala.
“We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connectivity of South America’s spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” he said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were located on the transverse axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two aimed at a larger connection with Ecuador although he did not give the most detailed details.
Similarly, the final document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that this country's electoral process will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," of which he is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and with good relations with its neighbors is another topic discussed at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart Daniel Ortega next Saturday in Mexico to quietly discuss the maritime dispute through a ruling of the ICC requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow I will have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We will review all these ways, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will ask for a discussion with this country," he said.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will settle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos said.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico, where they planned to attend the takeover of power by the country’s new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, as part of the summit, the bloc’s defence ministers will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen defence dialogue and consensus in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of Unasur, although the latter is suspended.
Peru holds the pro-tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
