So even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he was voiceless."
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their disease, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "exhausted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, in any case after the first cases, "the great victory is today that the survival of a patient who started treatment at the right time and the survival of the general population is exactly the same," said the head of the HIV unit of HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva and he takes for reference that this information was validated in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectiologist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a deadly disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depends on the level of immune system damage presented by patients at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for non-drug users: up to 30 years for a CD4 rate of 200 and up to 50 years for those reaching a CD4 rate of 500.
To put it simply, this means that for someone who would get a HIV positive diagnosis at the age of 25, “as long as he remains under control, he can live up to 75 years without problems,” the scientist explained.
In order to bring this progress back into its context, it is necessary to know that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
While it is true that mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died as a result of AIDS has increased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the annual report of UNAIDS), but it is also true that, since the onset of AIDS, 60% of patients recorded on the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths by May of this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
So why are there still deaths?
The problem is not access to treatment.
This is what happened in our hospital.
Over the last 12 years at least, we have never missed medication, the problem is that patients arrive at very advanced stages because they do not know they are infected, or they learn it at advanced stages of the disease.
He gives us an indisputable fact “nine out of ten patients arrive while they already have an opportunistic infection, what is needed to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to make earlier diagnoses and, for this, it is necessary to offer screening tests in a massive way, to all people who ask for it.”
Specialists and members of the State AIDS Prevention Council of Jalisco (Coesida) agree on his proposal, as do patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to take his screening test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done it and that, despite his young age, he was already a carrier of AIDS and suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancer tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you learn that you have AIDS.
Some think they’re going to die and don’t want to know anything.
"If I'm going to die, it's better to break out three times a week," they say, it's not my case.
The change has been beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medications.
So far, his parents only know that he has cancer.
I have a normal life, like anyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but co-responsible, I pay attention to myself and the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, thanks to his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the World AIDS Day march.
Let them do the test, if they have taken risks, the sooner they will know if they are HIV-positive and the better it will be, and if they already have the diagnosis, they need to know that one can live like everyone else, being responsible.
His message summarizes the slogan of the fight against AIDS in this year 2012.
Preservatives on the counter
There are many gaps between health programs and the ordinary citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara journalist who embraced the cause of HIV.
The most important thing is prevention.
In all places dedicated to this, "we have actually increased the distribution of condoms, before they gave us one or two, now they give us packs of a hundred, it is very good, but it results, that today, some still do not have access to condoms," he says.
