Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of local basketball history as large as that of Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason for this is that before a cerebral hemorrhage sentenced him to the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for over 60 years, whether as a player of lower leagues, a player of the national basketball team, manager and leader of the national team, the BSN, with the Bayamón Vaqueros or as president of the basketball federation.
"I've worn several basketball hats throughout my life, and even several at the same time, like when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s," Reyes recalls during a visit from Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he lives with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
Basketball is my whole life.
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes this claim.
The walls of his home, almost all decorated with photos and memories that remind him of his unusual itinerary, testify to this.
Bayamón in the Heart
Of all his memories, those he loves most are those that remind him of his passage as a player in the Vaqueros team in the mid-1950s until 1982, after spending 15 years as co-manager or manager of the team.
“These were my best years, those of which I had the most benefit because I had the chance to participate in eight Vaqueros championships from 1967 onwards, whether as manager, co-manager or manager.
This has been many years of satisfaction, including the five championships played from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired from the championship in 1981, the year that Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great manager, took the head of the team," says Reyes.
I remember that Gene Bartow, who had been running here and who was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said to me, “I have a tough player for you, he measures two meters.
Do you want it?”
This is how to start Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended me Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and who was one of the best shooters.
I remember he said that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win a championship, Gausse would help us try to win another.
He was delighted with the Vaqueros championship with Gausse, but only at a distance since in 1988 he was already the grand manitou of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of his and Mincy’s duties in the national team.
I remember when we won it for the first time in the United States at the pre-olympic tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we came fourth and where we should have won the bronze medal if this Canadian referee hadn’t made us play the last game again,” Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you’ve ever seen?
She is one of the best, just like the one who defeated the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favourite is that of the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won gold and we kicked the U.S. team, which was quite similar to the one that won the bronze at the World Cup.
This team was not only made up of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the 90 World Cup due to a knee problem.
A team that may not have been the best in terms of individuals, but they gave us a gold medal and great joy at the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like “Canito” Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner replacing the players suspended by the Pan-American Games in Mar del Plata, we won gold against all predictions.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, this is Piculín Ortiz.
His statistics on international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated this level as Piculín did.
And that without considering his trajectory in the various leagues for which he played.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
This is very difficult to say.
We had a good team consisting of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
In young people, I like the work that Leo Arill does.
What is your biggest achievement within the Federation?
Having been part of the most glorious time of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s the BSN had up to 17 teams in a season.
What do you still have to do?
There are things I would have wanted to put in place, such as the regionalization of minor categories.
For example, the Ponce boys play only in their area and only face teams from other corners of the island in the national play-offs.
Today, young people travel and play too much while this is not necessarily necessary.
I have at least seen the advantage of mandatory certifications and courses for executives, field staff and referees.
It makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
I generally listen to music, watch clips from my time on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and, from time to time, watch basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been by my side.
Actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born on September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became world famous for the lead role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he played a scrupulous, fearful and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the scrupulous oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of avarice in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year in the role of J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday night of complications from cancer, according to a statement from the family sent to The Associated Press for Warner Bros., the production house of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his dear hometown of Dallas, playing the ironic role he loved most," the family said.
Larry’s family and close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played her wife's role in the original series and in the sequel, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, her press agent, Jeffrey Lane, said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him very much.
"He was an exceptional person and he lived life deeply," Gray said in a statement.
Doctors diagnosed Larry Hagman with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and he had admitted to drinking a lot for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant liver tumor and had undergone a transplant.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman made himself known on television in the role of an ordinary guy in the series "Jinny of My Dreams" broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered a seductive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and he brought her home.
He also starred in two comedies that stayed shortly on the air, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among his film roles are critically acclaimed roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of the deliciously disgusting J.R. that Larry Hagman had his greatest success.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and their relatives was aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who Killed J.R.?", invented to maintain the suspense around an emotional episode in which Hagman's character is almost murdered, has generated worldwide speculation and millions of dollars played in bets.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached a record audience at that time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screens and made Dallas the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had gathered 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.’s sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had pregnant her and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but other people also had reasons to assault her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man with a charismatic smile: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who was trying to intern his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray).
“I know what would be needed as an epitaph for J.R,” Hagman said in 1988.
It should be written: “Here is the honest citizen J.R. Ewing.”
This is the only part he has lost.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, recalled on Friday Hagman as a "immense man, both on the small screen and in life."
He is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of each of us, who have had the chance to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were aired a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five episodes has already been completed for the second season and a sixth is underway, the channel said.
So far, neither Warner nor TNT have announced how Hagman’s death will be included in the series.
Originally from Fort Worth, Texas, he is the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who became famous with classical works such as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
Mary Martin was still a teenager when she gave birth in 1931 when she was married to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He made his first steps on the scenes of New York theaters in the early 1950s and served in the Air Force from 1952 to 1956 in England.
It was there that he met the young Swedish interior designer Maj Axelsson and married him.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for many years in the California town of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he titled his memoirs “Hello Darlin: Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life.”
"I have not written anything in this book that could hurt anyone or affect them in any way," he told the press at the time.
After his liver transplant, he became an active organ donation activist and worked as a volunteer in a hospital to assist concerned patients.
“I advise them, I restore them confidence, I come with them when they come for surgery and after,” he said in 1996.
I’m trying to offer them some comfort, like “Don’t be afraid, it won’t be easy for a moment, but it’s going to go well.”
He has also been an anti-tobacco activist and participated in several campaigns.
A course on the “End of the World” has just begun
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear warfare, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when the professor of religion Stuart Charmé decided to give a lesson on the end of the world, he knew that he was throwing an irresistible hammer there: the end of the "great count" of the Maya calendar, on December 21, which many people refer to as evidence of the imminent end of the world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea of what awaited him in the following months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal abyss that some have dubbed “the Armageddon of Debt” and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where end-time Christian theorists thought the apocalypse would unleash.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," Charmé told his students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey.
If you analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and tell it, it was a very good time.
And we must remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he’s not the only teacher to give classes on “the end of the world” this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
In Temple, assistant professor Barry Vacker gives the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear warfare, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We are analyzing this because these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides certain human behavior.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared to real-life examples.
“I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible,” Vacker said.
On Pennsylvania State University’s main campus, Latin American History professor Matthew Restall and colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply titled “The End of the World.”
"We're adding '2012' to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world't disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students have to study, create projects, and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work "until the very night of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
The courses proved to be quite popular.
"It was completed in two hours," Restall said about his course for high-level students, consisting of 35 students.
We received emails several weeks before the start of the semester, from people asking if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves," says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden University.
For the fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or of lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student of psychology and nursing, claims to have seen all the apocalyptic movies.
“I had never heard of a class that taught this subject,” he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students surveyed, let alone a professor, told us to believe in the end of the world on December 21.
“Our first project dealt with Maya prophecy, and in a way we discredited it,” said Julie Zegle, a 21 year old graduate student from Temple, West Chester.
The Maya never predicted the end of the world, it’s just a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I admit that there is an apocalyptic-related anxiety in Western culture, dating back several centuries, which causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has sparked the rise of this speculation.
“In other parts of the globe, people don’t think about that,” he assures.
This is mostly the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who teaches in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew there were classes on “the end of the world.”
“The Philippines is not participating in the end of the world,” he replied, as if it was an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall notes that over the years, there has been talk of the many supposed dates of the Last Judgment, and he says that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately begin to think about the next date" or philosophize that December 21 marks the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and teachers take the date lightly.
Many have told us that they thought they were going to “the end of the world” parties.
“Sometimes I call friends and we laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
